There is none of that. 
I have that! I have the receipts you do not!
Instead, the entire structure appears suddenly and fully formed in mid-2025,  exactly when lifecycle-based credential architectures first hit the public record.
If the ideas were truly pre-existing, the internet would show:
GitHub branches
archived RFC discussions
mailing list debates
commit histories
researcher commentary
But nothing exists.
X402 simply cannot explain this gap.
Bottom Line
If X402 really came from the old HTTP 402 error code, then the team behind it needs to explain:
how a placeholder status from 1997 suddenly gained
lifecycles, governance logic, execution authority, revocation semantics, and agent integration
all in the same quarter as every other major platform;
why no part of the lineage exists prior to 2025;
how dozens of unrelated industries somehow “invented” the same system simultaneously.
Until someone can answer those questions with verifiable evidence,
X402 looks less like a standard, and more like a retrofit narrative pasted onto lifecycle functions that originated elsewhere. Proof talks, BS walks!
